{
  "id": "custody-confidential-compute",
  "name": "Sealed Use",
  "desc": "Confidential compute and multi-party computation separate use from custody: computation happens on data no party fully sees. Processing without possession — the envelope is sealed, but the answer comes out.",
  "picks": {
    "Capability Class": {
      "value": "Tool-grade",
      "memo": "Confidential compute applies to tool-grade systems where the use-without-custody architecture matters more than frontier capability levels.",
      "detail": "Tool-grade capability is the baseline because the confidential compute argument is about custody architecture, not capability frontiers. The separation of use from custody works regardless of whether the underlying system is narrow or superhuman. What matters is the architectural principle that processing can occur without the processor possessing the data. Tool-grade keeps the stance focused on the custody innovation rather than capability dynamics."
    },
    "Domain Breadth": {
      "value": "Single-domain",
      "memo": "Confidential compute is illustrated in single-domain contexts where the use-without-custody architecture can be cleanly demonstrated without cross-domain complexity.",
      "detail": "Single-domain focus keeps the confidential compute demonstration architecturally clean and practically comprehensible. The principle of use without custody applies across domains but is most clearly illustrated in bounded contexts. Domain breadth does not affect the fundamental architectural claim that processing can be separated from possession. Single-domain picks emphasize the custody innovation without introducing unnecessary analytical complexity."
    },
    "Capability Trajectory": {
      "value": "Incremental",
      "memo": "Confidential compute operates under incremental trajectory because the custody architecture is independent of capability acceleration dynamics entirely.",
      "detail": "Incremental trajectory means the use-without-custody architecture does not depend on rapid capability improvement for relevance. Confidential compute works the same whether the underlying technology improves slowly or quickly. The architectural innovation is structural, not temporal, making trajectory a secondary consideration. Incremental trajectory signals that this is an architecture argument, not a capability race argument."
    },
    "Research Automation": {
      "value": "Human-led",
      "memo": "Confidential compute operates in human-led research contexts where the architecture question is about custody separation, not research automation dynamics.",
      "detail": "Human-led research is the baseline because confidential compute's custody innovation does not depend on AI research automation. The separation of use from custody is a cryptographic and architectural achievement, not an AI capability achievement. Human researchers design and implement the confidential compute environments that enable custody separation. Research automation level is orthogonal to the fundamental custody architecture argument."
    },
    "Unhobbling": {
      "value": "Tool-using",
      "memo": "Confidential compute applies to tool-using systems where the processing tools operate within the secure enclave without accessing data outside the boundary.",
      "detail": "Tool-using unhobbling means the system accesses computational tools within the secure enclave that processes data without exposing it. The tools operate on encrypted or enclave-protected data without the tool operator gaining custody of the underlying content. Tool-using level demonstrates that practical computation is possible within the confidential compute custody separation. The unhobbling level shows that use-without-custody is operationally real, not merely theoretically possible."
    },
    "Replication Scale": {
      "value": "Single instance",
      "memo": "Confidential compute is demonstrated with single-instance deployment where the custody separation architecture is most clearly and cleanly visible.",
      "detail": "Single instance simplifies the confidential compute demonstration by showing custody separation for one specific computation context. Multiple instances would introduce distributed trust complexity that would obscure the fundamental custody architecture argument. The single-instance focus makes the use-without-custody principle concrete and practically understandable. Single instance is the clearest setting for demonstrating that processing does not require data possession."
    },
    "Operating Speed": {
      "value": "Human-speed",
      "memo": "Confidential compute operates at human-speed where the cryptographic overhead of custody separation is manageable within normal processing timelines.",
      "detail": "Human-speed operation means the cryptographic protocols that enable use without custody operate within normal interactive timelines. The computational overhead of homomorphic encryption, secure enclaves, or MPC protocols is absorbed within acceptable latency bounds. Human-speed processing demonstrates that confidential compute is practically deployable, not merely a theoretical construction. The operating speed pick grounds the custody architecture in real-world operational feasibility."
    },
    "Physical World Extension": {
      "value": "Cognitive-only",
      "memo": "Confidential compute is cognitive-only, operating entirely in the digital computation domain where custody separation through cryptography is architecturally achievable.",
      "detail": "Cognitive-only extension means confidential compute operates in the digital computation domain where cryptographic custody separation works. The separation of use from custody is specifically a digital architecture capability that does not extend to physical possession. Physical-world data ultimately requires physical custody, but digital data can be processed without possession through cryptographic means. Cognitive-only focus demonstrates the specific domain where use without custody is architecturally possible."
    },
    "Role": {
      "value": "Tool",
      "memo": "The confidential compute system functions as a tool that processes data within a secure boundary without the tool operator gaining custody of inputs.",
      "detail": "Tool role means the system performs computation as directed without exercising independent agency over the data it processes. The operator directs the computation but the confidential compute architecture prevents them from accessing the underlying data. Tool role emphasizes that the system is a processing instrument, not a custodian of the data it processes. This role distinction is the operational expression of the use-without-custody principle."
    },
    "Actuation": {
      "value": "Digital action",
      "memo": "Confidential compute actuates through digital computation channels where the processing produces results without exposing input data to the processor.",
      "detail": "Digital action means the system performs computation that produces outputs without exposing the input data to the operator. The actuation is computational transformation within a secure boundary that maintains custody separation throughout processing. Digital action within confidential compute demonstrates that consequential data processing does not require data access. The actuation channel is where the use-without-custody principle becomes operationally and commercially meaningful."
    },
    "Autonomy": {
      "value": "Stateless task",
      "memo": "Confidential compute operates as stateless tasks where each computation is independently secured without persistent state that could compromise custody separation.",
      "detail": "Stateless task means each computation within the confidential compute environment starts fresh without carrying forward state from previous interactions. This prevents accumulation of data access beyond what each individual computation authorizes within the secure boundary. Stateless operation ensures that the custody separation is maintained across interactions, not just within a single computation. The stateless character means use-without-custody is continuously enforced rather than granted once."
    },
    "Delegated Authority": {
      "value": "Limited mandate",
      "memo": "Confidential compute receives a precisely limited computational mandate where authority is bounded by what the secure enclave permits without exposing data.",
      "detail": "Limited mandate means the computation is authorized to perform specific operations on data without gaining access to the data itself. The mandate is architecturally enforced by the confidential compute environment rather than merely contractually bounded. This architectural enforcement is what makes use-without-custody practically reliable rather than merely legally asserted. Limited mandate through architectural enforcement demonstrates custody separation that is stronger than any contractual delegation."
    },
    "Tool Access": {
      "value": "Gated tools",
      "memo": "Confidential compute gates tool access through the secure enclave boundary, allowing computation tools to operate on data without the tools exposing data externally.",
      "detail": "Gated tools means computational functions are available within the secure boundary but cannot move data outside the enclave. The gates are architecturally enforced by hardware attestation, encryption, or MPC protocols rather than by policy. Tool access within confidential compute demonstrates that useful computation can occur within architecturally enforced custody separation. Gated tool access is the practical mechanism through which use without custody becomes computationally useful."
    },
    "Response / Intervention Capability": {
